This goes along with #31386, but since that thread as been locked, I started a new one.

I'm having the same issue described in that thread with the difference being that I'm not using a template name for the `@ViewChild` selector, I'm using the component type.

``` javascript
// Instead of this:
@ViewChild('templateName', { static: false }) childComponent: MyChildComponent;

// I have:
@ViewChild(MyChildComponent, { static: false }) childComponent: MyChildComponent;
```
I have a `StubChildComponent` that I'm using in my tests, and following info found [here](https://indepth.dev/angular-unit-testing-viewchild/#adding-a-provider-to-the-stub-component), define a provider to use the stub component in place of my real one.
``` javascript
TestBed.configureTestingModule({
  declarations: [ ComponentUnderTest, StubChildComponent ],
  providers: [
    { provide: MyChildComponent, useClass: StubChildComponent }
  ]
})
.compileComponents();
```
If I change `ComponentUnderTest` to either use `static: true` or use a named template instead of the component type, the tests work correctly. However, I can't use `static: true` because the `MyChildComponent` is conditionally displayed with `*ngIf`, and while I can use a named template (and probably will for now), I don't like the idea of changing the app code in order to support the tests.

Not sure if this is a bug, or if there is a different way I should be configuring my tests to handle this situation.

